[2] Cholera - Angola (Luanda)
Date: Wed, 22 Feb 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Reuters [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/IRIN/ecbcd6cee890e0f6bfae1e673a43949b
.htm>

Cholera, a disease associated with poor sanitation and access to
potable water has claimed 8 lives in a suburb of the Angolan capital,
Luanda. The WHO said that 40 cases of the highly contagious disease,
spread through contaminated water or food, were reported in the last
few days in the Boavista shantytown located to the north of the
capital.
The provincial government of Luanda and the Angolan Ministry of
Health were alerted after an increase in diarrhea cases was reported
at a local health center. Subsequent epidemiological surveys
confirmed the existence of cholera.
Boavista is renowned among Luandans for its appalling living
conditions. Mud huts and corrugated iron structures are perched
precariously on piles of rubbish. There is no supply of potable water
and few homes can boast a latrine. WHO has described the area as
"totally unhealthy."
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
