[3] Cholera - Sudan (Central Equatoria State)
Date: Tue, 21 Feb 2006
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Independent Online [edited]
<http://www.iol.co.za>

The death toll from a suspected cholera outbreak in southern Sudan
has risen to 68 but the fatality rate of the epidemic is on the
decline, the UN's health agency said on Tue, 21 Feb 2006.
"As of 19 Feb 2006, a total of 2933 cases and 68 deaths (case
fatality rate 2.27 percent) of Acute Watery Diarrhea were reported in
Southern Sudan," the WHO said in a statement.
The outbreak has hit 2 major southern Sudanese towns, the
administrative capital Juba and Yei near the border with Uganda.
Cholera was confirmed in a number of deadly diarrhea cases.
The first case of Acute Watery Diarrhea was reported in Juba on 6 Feb 2006.
The Sudanese authorities and WHO have formed a joint task force to
combat the spread of the outbreak.
Health officials have warned of catastrophe if cholera spreads
through Juba, a city of about 250 000 people that relies almost
entirely on untreated water from the heavily-polluted Nile.
--
