[5] Diarrhea - Botswana (northern districts)
Date: Thu, 23 Feb 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Government of Botswana web site [edited]
<http://www.gov.bw/cgi-bin/news.cgi?
d=20060223&i=Botswana_enlists_US_experts_in_diarrhoea_fight>

Experts from American CDC are in Botswana to help carry out further
investigations on the diarrhea outbreak.
Francistown City Council (FCC) public health specialist Dr Refeletswe
Lobelonyane told a Francistown full council meeting that the health
ministry was forced to ask for outside intervention. She said on Tue,
21 Feb 2006, that CDC staff was already in Francistown to try to
establish the cause of the outbreak. They will send the stools for
further investigations in the US, where they have advanced
laboratories.
She said the outbreak has been reported in 10 districts mainly in the
northern part of the country with Serowe/Palapye being the worst-hit
in terms of morbidity and mortality. Lobelonyane said Francistown had
reported more cases but there were fewer deaths compared to other
districts.
Nyangabgwe referral hospitals pediatrics ward which has a 40-bed
capacity, had 93 patients, all on IV fluids. She told councillors
that several investigations have been carried out to determine the
cause of the outbreak. Investigations were carried out on water,
formula milk and Tsa bana [a weaning formula] which seem to be common
to infants but definitely the outbreak is not cholera.
--
